entry.title: Revert "Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API""
entry.content:
This reverts commit 9fd417a399dfb28ace5add2fa7df714f70de5bb6.



Reason for revert: The added unit tests fail on the Linux CFI bot

Failing tests: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20CFI/25348/overview



Original change's description:

> Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"

>

> This is a reland of commit e29465230b2f97fc64d51395bf9353e2ab266570

>

> This reland fixes the build issue on win-arm64 bots, such as [1], by

> declaring the missing arm64 intrinsics if the arm64intr.h is not

> included correctly due to LLVM issue [2]. Once the LLVM issue is

> resolved, this work-around should be removed.

>

> [1]: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8779781271284246545

> [2]: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/62942

>

> Original change's description:

> > pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API

> >

> > pthreadpool is used by XNNPACK which in turns supports TFLite and WebNN

> > to execute each neural network operator of a model by multiple threads

> > in parallel.

> >

> > To avoid creating an unmanaged thread pool owned by pthreadpool

> > implementation, this CL implements a shim of `pthreadpool_parallelize()`

> > that maps the pthreadpool thread tasks to work items and uses Jobs API

> > (`base::PostJob`) to schedule these work items with Chromium's

> > `base::ThreadPool` workers.

> >

> > According to the test result on a multi-core device, when scheduling 4

> > work items with `base::ThreadPool`, XNNPACK model inference performance

> > could get ~1.9X speedup for MobileNet V2 and ~2.8X speedup for ResNet50

> > V2 compared to single thread execution. And the test result also shows

> > using Jobs API shim could achieve 85% and 97% performance of using

> > pthreadpool own thread pool implementation for MobileNet V2 and ResNet50

> > V2 respectively.

> >

> > This CL also enables pthreadpool_unittests with Jobs API integration on

> > Windows and Linux bots that aligns with the `build_tflite_with_xnnpack`

> > build flag.

> >

entry.title: [aw] Add a feature to reset the draw functor in background.
entry.content:
When a WebView becomes invisible, the tiles required for the next frame

are still retained, for as long as the WebView is alive. In particular,

unlocked compositor frame reclaim doesn't work for WebView, contrary to

Chrome.



In practice, this means that we retain ~17MiB of tiles for each

fullscreen WebView which exists on a given device at a time (for a 1440p

device, here on Pixel 6 Pro). A solution to not keep this memory is to

release the draw functor after some time in background. This triggers a

context destroyed notification (DrawFn_OnContextDestroyed), resulting in

SkiaOutputSurfaceImpl getting destroyed, and then all tiles being

released.

entry.title: dlp: Data controls allows WebProtect access
entry.content:
In a enviroment with data controls and WebProtect data controls has to

allow WebProtect to read files for its checks. Otherwise the dlp daemon

would block reading the files. Data controls do not perform actual

checks of the destination URL. As for those call paths the content of

the files are only used to execute WebProtext checks and is not uploaded

to other external servers.



The accesses by client_side_* are not handled for now.

entry.title: Restrict process reuse for ProcessPerSiteUpToMainFrameThreshold
entry.content:
DevTools has an assumption that there is only one frame per renderer

process. This assumption doesn't hold when, for example, being over process limit, OOPIFs, and ProcessPerSite is enabled. These resulting in

unexpected renderer hangs when the feature is enabled and DevTools is

attached. The ProcessPerSiteUpToMainFrameThreshold feature makes this

much more likely to happen in practice for main frames.



To work around the problem, this CL makes following changes:

* Don't reuse a process when DevTools is attached.

* Don't reuse a renderer process for localhost or IP address based hosts

unless a field parameter explicitly allows it.

Note that these aren't complete solutions, but rather temporary and

incomplete workaround, with the purpose of mitigating this enough to get

data from a 1% stable experiment, before investing in a proper fix.

Also note that attaching devtools later, after the final process

assignment decision has been made, would still be broken. Another CL

[1] works around the issue.



[1] https://crrev.com/c/4582356

entry.title: [omnibox] Sanitize history suggestion titles.
entry.content:
Page titles can contain unsanitized characters (e.g. new lines or other

non-vanilla whitespace). We have DCHECKs in place to ensure match

contents and descriptions do not contain bad characters:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/omnibox/browser/autocomplete_result.cc;l=256-261;drc=3956eae144e19077ae5ad5908dee5463cd070a89



Some providers (e.g. document provider) enforce by calling

`AutocompleteMatch::SanitizeString()`.



Other providers enforce this some other way; e.g. the bookmark provider

removes bad characters from bookmarks with titles containing them -

though I didn't investigate how it does so.



But the HQP and HUP don't. E.g., if you 1) create a local html file

containing `bad space`, 2) open the page in

chromium, then 3) type 'b' into the omnibox, the DCHECKs crash.



This CL fixes those crashes by calling `SanitizeString()` when HQP and

HUP set their matches' titles.



I considered doing it upstream (i.e. for all history DB reads), but

there were too many callsites and it didn't seem worthwhile to go

through all of them and ensure they'd work as expected with the

sanitized strings.

entry.title: inputs: Keep Lacros ConfirmComposition fixes if Ash requires them.
entry.content:
Lacros will apply some bug fixes for ConfirmComposition when the

following flags are enabled:

- WaylandCancelComposition

- WaylandKeepSelectionFix



Ash has a flag called AlwaysConfirmComposition that depends on the two

flags above. Without them, AlwaysConfirmComposition will cause a severe

regression.



Therefore, if Ash has AlwaysConfirmComposition enabled, Lacros must

enable the bug fixes, even if the flags are off. Lacros needs to read

the state of AlwaysConfirmComposition via ash_capabilities.



Although we could make both Ash and Lacros use the same

AlwaysConfirmComposition flag, WaylandKeepSelectionFix and

WaylandCancelComposition are useful fixes on their own as well, so we

want them to be independent of each other.



This makes it safe to disable these flags independently to avoid the

critical regression caused by version skew last time.



HOW TO REVERT:

1. Find the culprit CL via a bisect.

2A. If the culprit is AlwaysConfirmComposition, just revert it by itself. The issue will be fixed once Ash deploys.

2B. If the culprit is WaylandCancelComposition/WaylandKeepSelectionFix, revert all three flags: WaylandCancelComposition, WaylandKeepSelectionFix, AlwaysConfirmComposition. The issue will be fixed once both Lacros and Ash deploys.

entry.title: WebNN: Implement CommandRecorder::Open() for DirectML backend
entry.content:
This CL implements `CommandRecorder::Open()` that prepares the

underlying command list and command allocator for new command recording.

After recording the commands, the caller calls the

`CommandRecorder::CloseAndExecute()` method to submit the recorded

command list to the command queue for GPU execution. The caller is

allowed to open the command recorder without waiting for the GPU to

complete execution of previous recorded commands. For example,

JavaScript code may compute a WebNN graph without waiting for the

promise of the previous compute call to be resolved. The

`CommandRecorder::Open()` method would ensure the command allocator is

not reset while the previous command list is still being used by the

GPU.



To simplify the error handling code, this CL implements

RETURN_IF_FAILED() and RETURN_NULL_IF_FAILED() macros in error.h.



For unit tests, this CL adds MultipleSubmissionsWithOneWait of

WebNNCommandRecorderTest to test this scenario. To simplify the command

recorder tests, this CL also implements some helpers for different GPU

buffers’ creation.

entry.title: Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit e29465230b2f97fc64d51395bf9353e2ab266570



This reland fixes the build issue on win-arm64 bots, such as [1], by

declaring the missing arm64 intrinsics if the arm64intr.h is not

included correctly due to LLVM issue [2]. Once the LLVM issue is

resolved, this work-around should be removed.



[1]: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8779781271284246545

[2]: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/62942



Original change's description:

> pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API

>

> pthreadpool is used by XNNPACK which in turns supports TFLite and WebNN

> to execute each neural network operator of a model by multiple threads

> in parallel.

>

> To avoid creating an unmanaged thread pool owned by pthreadpool

> implementation, this CL implements a shim of `pthreadpool_parallelize()`

> that maps the pthreadpool thread tasks to work items and uses Jobs API

> (`base::PostJob`) to schedule these work items with Chromium's

> `base::ThreadPool` workers.

>

> According to the test result on a multi-core device, when scheduling 4

> work items with `base::ThreadPool`, XNNPACK model inference performance

> could get ~1.9X speedup for MobileNet V2 and ~2.8X speedup for ResNet50

> V2 compared to single thread execution. And the test result also shows

> using Jobs API shim could achieve 85% and 97% performance of using

> pthreadpool own thread pool implementation for MobileNet V2 and ResNet50

> V2 respectively.

>

> This CL also enables pthreadpool_unittests with Jobs API integration on

> Windows and Linux bots that aligns with the `build_tflite_with_xnnpack`

> build flag.

>

entry.title: Add additional check to block race condition
entry.content:
It is possible, though unlikely, for a second request to come through

*after* a request has been served (e.g. the runtime is presenting and

the request_session_callback_ has been nulled out). This request should

be rejected as there is now an active immersive session; though the

browser process may not know it yet. (e.g. the request got queued up

while the previous request was processing and so the browser process

was as yet unaware of the result).

entry.title: Allow video stream to end when paused and no frames remain.
entry.content:
The fix for https://crbug.com/935451 introduced a regression here. The

intent was to try and obey frame duration with regards to when we signal

the ended event. However when time isn't progressing, we should signal

ended right away instead of waiting until playback starts.



The HTML5 spec says: "It is possible for a media element to have both

ended playback and paused for user interaction at the same time." which

implies we should fire ended when reaching the last frame while paused.
